labels.label:
Tested value is less than estimated.
That means that the query is still retrieving results,
so delay a few seconds and then try again
Loop to Page Through Results

For APIs that need a POST request with the user/pw contained in the body, 
InvokeHTTP currently uses flowfile content to populate the body. 
However flowfile content cannot be set with sensitive parameters and so there 
is no way to hide those values. The approach here is to put that information
within processors in a process group and then that process group could have its 
access control set so only those with rights to see that process group 
could view those contents.
 
Currently I have a feature request open for the need to be able to set the 
body content with sensitive values and the moderators agreed in the 
comments that it is something that should be incorporated in a future 
release of the InvokeHTTP processor. 
 
(More details at 
https://issues.apache.org/jira/projects/NIFI/issues/NIFI-11331?filter=allopenissues)

The row-count attribute is sent in the body of the post, 
but because this is a mock API, we are also appending 
the row-start to the end of the URL in order to more 
easily simulate getting paged results.
Loop until results are ready

When data doesn't return, to ensure that there are truly no more results,
above loop cycles a few more times.
 
Any empty records that result are sent here and discarded.

Since we are going against a mock API, this is 
an extra UpdateAttribute processor inserted in 
between the below processors in order to have 
it mock that the query is now complete and 
the flow can move on.

This script takes the previously extracted column names 
and matches them to the correct value, replacing the 
"text" key with the column name so that it can be treated 
as a record and loaded using record aware processors.

labels.label: Tanium DEV

If it is coming from one of the "Test FlowFile" GenerateFlowFile processors,
it routes it to the right side and bypasses the API calls.
Otherwise the it goes to the left and calls the API.
Tanium DEV

Set attributes specific to Data Subject.
(Here it sets the target table for
Manifest Patching Status).

The intent was to feed into one PutIceberg processor
and use the "target-table" attribute in the Table Name 
property, but PutIceberg does not allow Expression 
Language variables in its Table Name property and so 
had to end up adding this RouteOnAttribute just so 
that I could get this to work with that type of processor.
Patching Manifest
Tanium TEST

The DEV/TEST/PROD processors
 are disabled in both subject areas 
because currently they trigger 
InvokeHTTP calls that go against 
a free API mocking service that is 
rate limited and so if you enable 
these you need to choose 
"Run Once" to prevent using up all 
the calls for the day and having to 
wait for the next day.

There are two Tanium Data Subjects (Manifest Patching Status and Patching Manifest).
 
Each Data Subject has three Tanium API domain sources (DEV, TEST, and PROD).
 
Each Data Subject also has a Test FlowFile that can be used when 
needing to test and bypass calling the Tanium API.

parameters.name: CDP Workload User
parameters.description: Specify the CDP machine user or workload user name that you want to use to authenticate to Kafka and Hive. Ensure this user has the appropriate access rights in Ranger for the Kafka topic and ID Broker for Hive access.

parameters.name: Schema Registry Hostname
parameters.description: Specify the hostname of the Schema Registry you want to connect to. This must be the direct hostname of the Schema Registry itself, not the Knox Endpoint.

parameters.name: CSV Delimiter
parameters.description: If your source data is CSV, specify the delimiter here.

parameters.name: Data Input Format
parameters.description: Specify the format of your input data. You can use "CSV", "JSON" or "AVRO" with this ReadyFlow.

parameters.name: Hive Catalog Namespace
parameters.description: Specify the Hive Catalog Namespace. The default value is default, which references the database catalog created automatically when you activate an environment in Cloudera Data Warehouse.

parameters.name: Schema Name
parameters.description: Specify the schema name to be looked up in the Schema Registry for the Source Kafka Topic

parameters.name: CDP Workload User Password
parameters.description: Specify the password of the CDP machine user or workload user you're using to authenticate against Kafka and Hive.
